reviewText:
Early Access Review

Nostalgic to some, impressive to all, easy to none. Black Mesa is challenging. Black Mesa is hard. Black Mesa will eat your soul, but not before making you die a couple hundred times in-game. Black Mesa will send you back a few years, and punch you back to reality just as you start begging for more.

Why don't we have a robot or something to push this sample into the core? This looks sort of dangerous.

Gordon Freeman

Without any further delay, I present to you my review of Black Mesa.

GameplayIt’s not possible to talk about Black Mesa and not mention Half-Life, but to be honest, other than the lambda symbol, and all the internet memes, I’ve no knowledge of any of the HL games, so it’s safe to say I’m part of the 0,1% that never played them.
When I started my Black Mesa adventure, I wasn’t expecting top notch graphics, state of the art technology or anything alike, and that was a good thing, as I didn’t find those. What I did find was a great adventure, or, well, a great semi-adventure, as I was stopped by a “To be continued” screen, which left me wanting more, but not better. Why am I not wanting better, you may ask. The reason is quite simple actually. From shooting aliens, to killing headcrabs, to swimming in radioactive waste and even bombing a gigantic alien-octopus, there are very few things that can get better. And just when you think you’ve got it all under control, with all the overpowered weapons, it hits you, literally, and you’re back to square one, in a way.
I like to think a good story can make up for most of the stuff, but there was nothing to make up for with Black Mesa.
If I loved this game without being a previous Half-Life admirer, I’d say it’s pretty safe to say everyone can, and will, find this game extremely entertaining.


Pros Great story;
When compared to Half-Life games, there’s an obvious upgrade graphics wise;
Quite a few weapons available to annihilate humans and aliens alike;
Challenging, not only difficulty wise, but also with some, sort of, puzzles to solve;
Simple UI;
Some amazing screenshots can be obtained while playing;
Very fun, very creepy, very entertaining, and even very scary at points;
Various options to customize your character in multiplayer mode;
Active community and development team.
Considering it's an Early Access (EA) game, I've decided to add a Neutral" category

